Apr 19 2007 	Bang for the Buck	I’ve been going to Las Vegas since 1979. I believe that the first two times you visit, you should stay on the Strip, walk around with your eyes and mouth wide open, experience the overpriced hotels, tight slots, high minimums at the tables, and the underpaying video poker machines. By your third trip, you’re ready to stay Downtown. Which brings us to the Las Vegas Club. CHECK INSmooth, quick, efficient. When I requested to be away from the noise of Freemont Street, the check-in clerk showed me a map of the hotel and asked whether Room-X would be okay.THE ROOMI stayed in the SOUTH TOWER -- so all comments refer to the SOUTH TOWER only.The room was spacious. Two people can move around without bumping into each other. The paint, carpet, etc were in good condition. Drawers and closet space were sufficient. The bed was comfortable. The linens were clean.The bathroom was tiny; the sink was located outside the bathroom. The sink area contained adequate counter space. The shower stream was steady and strong. The water temperature was constant. The tub drained slowly, but I didn’t consider it an inconvenience.The A/C worked very well and very quietly. It was the type of A/C that didn’t turn on/off based on temperature. This will be a plus for those who wake up every time a heater/AC turns on or off.The television was small and carried only a few basic channels.There was no clock.The room contained a safe -- for me an important feature. You pay an additional $1.00 a day. Payment is on the honor system. At checkout, you’re asked whether you used the safe. If you want to die rich rather than poor, you can say that you didn’t use it and they’ll remove the charge from your bill.Here’s something that my wife always cares about, so I’ll mention it. There is no full-length mirror in the room.HOUSEKEEPINGI left the room in the morning. When I came back at night, the room had been cleaned. What more can I ask?ELEVATORSThere were two South Tower elevators. I was there seven days and never once even came close to thinking “What’s taking so long” . Very efficient.SECURITYNo one checks room keys as you enter the elevator. I failed to notice whether the elevators had a security camera. There was a security camera in the hotel corridor. There were security cameras in the parking garage.PARKINGThere is complimentary self-parking in their garage for hotel guests. There is also valet parking which I never investigated. The garage itself is roomy and easy to navigate.LOCATIONLocated at the top of Freemont Street, the Las Vegas Club is in the center of the action -- a very busy, very safe area.SUMMARYThink of The Wynn or Bellagio or Venetian as a top-of-the-line Lexus; whereas the Las Vegas Club is a Corolla -- a no frills dependable machine that gets you where you want to go economically and efficiently.	
