Apr 20 2006	Great value!	I stayed four nights in April at the Vegas Club. I was booked for the South Tower, but when I arrived I asked if I could instead stay in the North Tower---the desk clerk shrugged and said okay and gave me a free upgrade.The North Tower room fit my needs nicely. The room was surprisingly large, the bathroom had a shower/bath and a separate sink area. Most importantly, the bed was very comfortable. I'm a little picky about beds and this one had soft sheets and quality pillows.The room also had a safe (one dollar per day) and a little lounge area with a loveseat, two chairs and a table. The television had about fifteen channels----no HBO. My window faced north to the California hotel/casino....the views are probably better from the south-facing rooms.I didn't eat in any of the Vegas Club restaurants. I played some in the casino and was never offered a comp. The blackjack pit bosses are kind of jumpy----worried about card-counters.The Vegas Club location is almost ideal----there's the California and Main Street Station casinos behind the Vegas Club, the Plaza is just across the street, the Golden Gate and their great shrimp cocktails are just across Fremont, a few steps down are La Bayou and their huge selection of daiquiris, the Glitter Gulch nudie bar, and Mermaids little casino with their deep-fried Twinkies and Oreos. Down just a few more steps are Binion's and the Golden Nugget. I spent alot of time in most of these casinos....I even sat next to a guy at the Main Street Station who made $25,000 at blackjack in about two hours.I've stayed in the Luxor and the Monte Carlo previously....the Vegas Club doen't have the glitz and attractions that those places offer, but the room was nearly as nice at less than half the price. After three trips to Vegas I've decided I'm definitely a downtown guy----cheaper, better rules at the gambling tables, better payouts on video poker, and vastly easier to get around from casino to casino.	
