Apr 30 2005	Las Vegas Club fine for gamblers not snobs...	I stayed in one of the South Tower rooms for two nights in mid-April at the LVC. The room I stayed in had good water pressure, hot water, clean bedding, and enough space to walk around. The carpet could use replacing; although it had obviously been cleaned, the unmistakeable stain of *age* was evident. The bathroom was small, but I am talking about the room with the toilet and tub; the sink/mirror area is outside of this, with plenty of counter space to set neccesities on. At least in the room I stayed in, this sink area is semi-private from the rest of the room thanks to a partial wall. The beds at first looked like a lost cause, because they were very low to the ground. I must say, however, that those beds were some of the most comfortable I have ever slept on, much to my surprise. As for the gaming, the LVC is famous for low limits and good blackjack. Well, almost: the table with the sign for &quot;the world's most liberal blackjack game&quot; is for suckers only. Blackjacks are only paid 6:5 to the player, which drastically raises the house edge. Stick to the regular single deck game, which is usually only offered in the evenings. Incidentally, the casino is a bit of a maze. Even after staying there for two days, I found myself walking opposite of where I should've been. In the final analysis, LVC is a fair place to stay if you aren't picky, but for clean freaks the only place to stay downtown is the Golden Nugget.	
Apr 26 2005	Worse than a Motel 6	Don't stay at this hotel!!! I stayed at this hotel based on the recommendations on here - the consensus seemed to be that after the Golden Nugget this was the place to stay downtown.I booked a room for 5 nights at $50 a night - they say you get what you pay for, but this wasn't even worth the $50!When we arrived (with 4 suitcases) there was no bellhops to help with the luggage. Check in was slow and we were never told where our room was. When we got to the room there were cigarette burns all over the floor, the sheets had holes in them and we could feel every spring in the mattress. Our room was across from the ice machine and elevators and all you could hear was the &quot;clump clump clump&quot; of the ice going into buckets. I asked to get a room with a better mattress - the new room had only a slightly better bed. The rooms are a good size but they do not provide an alarm clock, hairdryer, or coffee pot - all things which are pretty standard for hotel rooms. The TV was small, the remote didn't work, there is no Internet access in the rooms. The decor is outdated, the bedspread looked like it hadn't been washed in a while. The sheets were not fitted so every time you got in bed they pulled off. Our bathtub didn't drain properly so when you took a shower you ended ankle deep in water. Our couch had a huge disgusting white stain on it - I have no idea what it was. I would not stay here again (despite the price). I travel all the time for business - and I usually stay in Holiday Inns or similar - I don't expect luxury - but I do expect a hotel to be at the least as &quot;nice&quot; as a Motel 6. I was EXTREMELY disappointed in this hotel.	
Apr 24 2005	A clean and quiet room for a price that can't be beat	This was our fourth trip to Las Vegas in the past four years, and our first time staying on Fremont Street. We picked the Las Vegas club because of the great price and the fact that it is under the Fremont Experience.The room was clean comfortable and quiet. We didn't have a view unless you count the parking garage as a view. The shower had more pressure and hot water than I could have dreamed. Room service employees were courteous. Check-in was posted at the desk for 3 pm. We showed up at 2 pm, no problem, they checked us in happily.The casino wasn't the most attractive place. The clientele appeared to be mostly locals. My wife and I preferred to do our gambling in the Nugget, 4 Queens, and Fremont Hotel. Thats the good part about Fremont Street hotels. You can walk to all the nearby casinos in a matter of minutes. Try walking to another casino if you're at the MGM Grand and you'll understand. Also, every night is a street party under the lights.We didn't eat at any of the restaurants Las Vegas Club so I can't comment on them. Restaurant prices were reasonable at the other places downtown, so I imagine they were the same here.All in all, we got what we got what we were looking for....a cheap place to stay and an experience hanging around downtown. From now on, we are going to always stay downtown, but perhaps we will try another hotel.	
Mar 29 2005	We'll be back!	1st visit to Vegas and I must admit that at first, I was disappointed not to be staying in one of the mega resorts on the Strip. But, after staying at the Las Vegas Club, I am very happy that I did. LVC was well worth the price. Our room in the North Tower was spacious, clean, and comfortable at a fantastic rate. The food at the Upper Deck Restaurant (2nd level) was not gourmet, but it was plentiful, satisfying, and inexpensive. The on site steakhouse (sorry, I forgot the name) was excellent. The dealers at the table were very helpful when I told them it was my first time. I liked the &quot;smallness&quot; of the LVC. Although I did go to the Strip to see the lights and catch a show (had to see Mamma Mia!), I very much enjoyed spending the bulk of my time and money at LVC. My friends &amp; I are planning a &quot;girls only&quot; trip to Vegas in October and have already decided to stay at LVC.	
