Jan 16 2004	You get what you pay for...	We wanted to spend one night of our Jan '04 Vegas holiday downtown, and the Las Vegas Club had some of the cheapest rates going. For $25 we had a room booked for a Sunday night, and based on reviews here we had reasonable expectations.When we checked in at around 5.30pm, we were told there were no king non-smoking rooms available - although that was what we'd booked - and would we take two queens instead? Not our first choice, but okay, we're flexible... We then asked for a North Tower room, knowing they were nicer than the South Tower ones, but alas, our cheap rate applied to the South Tower only. The next disappointment was finding that we would be on the second floor - ie. level with an adjacent roof, with no view except of that roof. You never feel quite as safe when someone can walk up to your window... but like I said, we're not overly fussy and didn't really want to make waves. It was one night and it was dirt cheap and we just wanted to get to the room.The room itself was adequate. Quite large, but getting a bit ratty around the edges. Marks on the carpet, beds with scuffed and stained bases, a chipped table. Older style bathroom with scratchy towels. Housekeeping had done an okay job of cleaning, but you can't remove all the signs of wear and tear.None of which is intended as a major complaint... we knew the hotel was older, we knew the South Tower rooms weren't as nice, we were prepared for a few scratches and scrapes. Downtown was interesting, and I understand why people like it, but I think we're Strip people at heart - so we'd be unlikely to stay at the LVC again. For the same money, we could have had another night at the Stratosphere, which was much newer and nicer - with friendlier staff.	
